# Architecture Details

## Layers

### Composition Root (App)
- Read launch options, init global services/configs/save/dev tools, create player, start/stop `RaidSession`, handle scene transitions.
- `App.Instance` allowed only here.

### Session Layer
- `Player`: persistent profile, meta progression, save/load entry point.
- `RaidSession`: owns `RaidState`/`LevelState`, constructs `RaidContext`, orchestrates manager execution in stable order.

### Domain Logic (Managers)
- Stateless static functions operating on explicit state and context.
- Accept inputs as arguments, mutate state via `ref`.
- Must not depend on hidden globals.

### Adapters (Ports)
- All Unity subsystem access (navmesh, physics, time) through interfaces passed via context.

### View / Presenter
- Translates state and domain events into transforms, animation, VFX, SFX, UI.
- Must not make gameplay decisions.

## Data flow

### State buckets
- `PlayerProfileState` (persistent), `RaidState` (per run), `LevelState` (per level/run).
- Values and IDs only. No Unity object references.

### Context (`RaidContext`)
- Read-only, passed as `in`. Contains: ports/adapters, config refs, event sink/buffer, constants (`dt`, masks, tuning).

### Events
- Managers emit domain-to-view intents through `IRaidEvents`. Presenter consumes them.

## Tick model
1. Gather input and external signals.
2. Run managers in deterministic order (movement → AI → combat → loot → extraction).
3. Produce state changes and domain events.
4. Present state and events in Unity.

## Entry points
All entry points (Menu, direct Level/Raid, test scenarios) go through `GameLauncher.Launch(LaunchOptions)`. Do not rely on directly loading arbitrary scenes.
